{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613062"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16301"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16301"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.21,0,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8992"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7493"},{"type":"tags","id":"7495"},{"type":"tags","id":"7502"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"},{"type":"tags","id":"10466"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular system contains specialised receptors that detect head position and movement. These receptors are located in different parts of the inner ear and serve distinct functions in maintaining balance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of receptors for dynamic equilibrium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ampullae of semicircular ducts","Maculae of utricle","Maculae of saccule","Cochlear duct","Endolymphatic sac"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eampullae of semicircular ducts\u003C/strong\u003E contain specialised sensory structures called cristae ampullaris, which are the receptors for dynamic equilibrium. These receptors detect rotational (angular) acceleration of the head in different planes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaculae of utricle\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emaculae of saccule\u003C/strong\u003E contain otolithic organs that detect linear acceleration and static head position relative to gravity. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecochlear duct\u003C/strong\u003E contains the organ of Corti for hearing, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Eendolymphatic sac\u003C/strong\u003E helps regulate endolymph fluid homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cristae ampullaris contain hair cells embedded in a gelatinous cupula. When the head rotates, endolymph movement deflects the cupula, stimulating the hair cells and signalling head rotation to the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dynamic equilibrium receptors (cristae ampullaris) are located in the ampullae of semicircular ducts and detect angular acceleration of the head.","Static equilibrium receptors (maculae) are found in the utricle and saccule and detect linear acceleration and head position relative to gravity."],"references":["Rabbitt RD. Semicircular canal biomechanics in health and disease. J Neurophysiol. 2019 Mar 1;121(3):732-755. doi: 10.1152/jn.00708.2018. Epub 2018 Dec 19. PMID: 30565972; PMCID: PMC6520623.","S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez de Nava A, Lasrado S. Physiology, Ear. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK540992/","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16301"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60123"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T23:18:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T00:01:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8992"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1992"},"attributes"